be more built into Corto. But aside from that, so far, I haven't encountered anything that is

00:46:12.719 --> 00:46:19.600
in no way to say the system is complete, just for my workflows. It has been, I've been able to like

00:46:19.600 --> 00:46:25.040
open issues and get them resolved so far, and I encourage you all to do the same, because this is

00:46:25.040 --> 00:46:32.320
kind of baby ages of Corto, and I think the team developing it is kind of really looking out for

00:46:33.199 --> 00:46:36.080
things people are struggling with so they can work on those next.

00:46:39.360 --> 00:46:41.120
I have another question from the floor.

00:46:45.600 --> 00:46:52.320
Hi, good morning, at least it's morning here. So thank you, this is great. You talk a lot about

00:46:52.320 --> 00:46:57.199
education, maybe it's the artwork that also makes me think of this, but do you have any intentions

00:46:57.199 --> 00:47:01.840
for getting this to a level that youth could learn from this as well?

00:47:04.719 --> 00:47:09.600
So that's a really nice question, and let me clarify, when you say youth, do you mean

00:47:09.600 --> 00:47:15.919
below the college level? Yes, yeah, I have young kids, so I'm thinking of them.

00:47:16.479 --> 00:47:22.159
Yes, yes, so I think that's a really good question. While I have limited experience

00:47:23.040 --> 00:47:30.800
with that, I have ran a few workshops for high school students, a few kind of conferences,

00:47:32.320 --> 00:47:38.239
StatFest that ASA runs, which is like a diversity-focused conference. I've done that there

00:47:38.239 --> 00:47:44.239
with some high school students, and I think that this sort of thing, with the visual editor

00:47:44.239 --> 00:47:51.600
particularly, is entirely, I think a real good way of introducing students to code. In the past,

00:47:52.639 --> 00:47:58.719
what I have used are LearnR tutorials for that, and the idea there was, I know that you can't do

00:47:58.719 --> 00:48:03.520
real data science outside of something like an IDE, but can you give them a taste of something

00:48:03.520 --> 00:48:09.840
outside of that? And I think the answer is yes, and the reason why I had kept things out of the

00:48:09.840 --> 00:48:16.879
RStudio IDE and done a LearnR tutorial was that I didn't also want to teach them markdown syntax,

00:48:16.879 --> 00:48:23.120
and I think with the visual editor, how it distinguishes between what's prose and what is

00:48:23.120 --> 00:48:29.520
code so distinctly, it would be worthwhile to try to bring that audience into that to see how they

00:48:29.520 --> 00:48:36.239
react to it. I personally have not had experience with that, but I will tell you that if you follow

00:48:36.239 --> 00:48:42.959
along with some of the stats education work that goes around, particularly presented at conferences

00:48:42.959 --> 00:48:48.000
like US COTS and ECOTS, there's always a group of people who are working with that crowd, and

00:48:48.000 --> 00:49:00.080
they're working on really neat things. Hi, I have a question about the collaboration. So you showed

00:49:00.080 --> 00:49:04.800
how you could, I guess, have people, different people, say, contribute different files, like,

00:49:04.800 --> 00:49:09.199
you know, somebody puts their Python notebook in this or whatever when you're building the website,

00:49:09.919 --> 00:49:16.320
which seems really interesting. I was wondering if there's any provision for, like, collaboratively

00:49:16.320 --> 00:49:21.360
editing the same document. So I'm imagining something like a Google Docs type interface

00:49:21.360 --> 00:49:26.800
where people are contributing to one document, or is it currently file-based in the sense that,

00:49:26.800 --> 00:49:32.560
like, you'd be needing something like Git on the back end to manage multiple contributions to one

00:49:32.560 --> 00:49:40.719
document? Yeah, great question. What I showed would have assumed something like Git, so you're

00:49:40.719 --> 00:49:45.840
absolutely right in that. When it comes to collaborative editing, so I have two answers

00:49:45.840 --> 00:49:53.840
for this. If you are working in RStudio, there is a collaborative editing functionality that's

00:49:53.840 --> 00:50:00.560
being developed for RStudio Cloud. It is my hope that it goes beyond just RStudio Cloud,

00:50:00.560 --> 00:50:07.360
and it's, I think, still a beta feature, but I would hope that in due time we're going to see a

00:50:07.360 --> 00:50:14.639
nice implementation of that in something like RStudio Server. I am not very well-versed,

00:50:14.639 --> 00:50:20.239
I'm afraid, in, like, VS Code. I don't use it regularly, but I feel like I follow enough people

00:50:20.239 --> 00:50:26.560
on Twitter that I see things that they share. So I think, I believe in VS Code you can do

00:50:26.560 --> 00:50:32.000
collaborative editing. Don't quote me on that, but I think it's worth googling, and if you don't

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:38.080
code in VS Code, obviously that may not be very helpful, but ultimately the fact that Corto is,

00:50:38.879 --> 00:50:44.959
like, authoring environment independent, I think means that you're not stuck in RStudio in the

00:50:44.959 --> 00:50:50.479
sense that if another editor has these sorts of bells and whistles that are useful for your

00:50:50.479 --> 00:50:56.479
workflow, you can take what has been developed at the command line interface level and use it there,

00:50:56.479 --> 00:51:00.560
and that portability hopefully, you know, allows for exploring

00:51:00.560 --> 00:51:03.280
some other solutions that might be useful in this case.

00:51:11.040 --> 00:51:13.120
And then we're going to have to close, so we have Leo.

00:51:13.760 --> 00:51:23.520
Hi, Minu, this is Leonardo. I'm very enthused by your presentation on Corto, so do you know if

00:51:25.439 --> 00:51:33.600
the vignette builders or in R are going to allow Corto vignettes? And then my second question would

00:51:34.159 --> 00:51:58.320
be, can you have two Corto files where they share the R code but you don't execute it in both at the same time, so you have, like, a HTML and a presentation that have the same R code behind it, but you don't have to spend the computational power to render it twice?

00:51:58.639 --> 00:52:23.600
So, question number one, vignette builders, I do not know the answer to this question. However, I think this is a good opportunity to point folks to where a good place for asking questions is. On the Corto GitHub repository, there's a GitHub discussions feature, so you can just have a question. It doesn't have to be an issue like a software bug.

00:52:23.760 --> 00:52:32.560
So, if you go to the Corto website and click on help, it will get you there, and that is a fantastic venue for that question, and I apologize that I don't have an answer for it.

00:52:32.560 --> 00:53:01.600
For the second question of having a single R source code for multiple kind of QMD files, if that's a workflow that you prefer, you can have include statements in your Corto file. So, it's just two curly braces and then include. And so, the way I would solve that problem is put the R code that you want in a third file that you then include where necessary, and that's a great way to do it.

00:53:02.639 --> 00:53:11.919
And you can do that at the level, but I imagine it's going to be interspersed through the text. So, I think you would want those includes statements interspersed through your text as well.

00:53:11.919 --> 00:53:34.000
I wish we had a little more time. Maybe I'll ask one more question, though. This has to do with books and how many examples there are of volumes that are satisfactorily produced in the Corto framework that are monographs and may include cross references between chapters and so forth, something we have found difficult to deal with.

00:53:34.000 --> 00:54:03.040
Yeah, so there are plenty actually, let me link to, and I'll put this in the chat here for folks to see. So, on the Corto website, you'll be able to go to the gallery where we've collected books and a handful of these also have PDF output as well. Personally, something I've struggled with in the past has been making things look good in HTML and in PDF, and I think that's a great way to do it.

00:54:03.040 --> 00:54:32.080
So, you'll be able to see examples of that. Corto is quite new, so the number is not in hundreds, but there is a growing number of them, and hopefully that gallery is inspirational in terms of solving that. Cross references and stuff, I've demoed that at the very end with the visual editor, not that you have to use the visual editor, but the same cross reference style works, whether it is a single document or it's a book or a website, which I think perhaps would be a good way to do it.

00:54:32.080 --> 00:54:38.080
And I think perhaps resolves some of those challenges with adding references to a book.

00:54:38.080 --> 00:54:45.080
Fantastic. I'm going to have to close the session because some of us have to change buildings. Thank you so much for a wonderful presentation.

00:54:45.080 --> 00:54:46.080
Thank you.

00:54:46.080 --> 00:54:50.080
Have a good day.

00:55:02.080 --> 00:55:03.080
Thank you.

00:55:32.080 --> 00:55:33.080
Thank you.

00:56:02.080 --> 00:56:03.080
Thank you.

00:56:32.080 --> 00:56:34.080
Thank you.

00:57:02.080 --> 00:57:04.080
Thank you.

00:57:32.080 --> 00:57:34.080
Thank you.

